<subSubSection pageId="50" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="50.[151,1437,151,1256]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,338,1015,1040]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Comments:</emphasis>
Within the 
<taxonomicName box="[491,791,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cavernosium">
<emphasis box="[491,791,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">Allometopon cavernosium</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
group, 
<taxonomicName box="[892,1060,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="phenomena">
<emphasis box="[892,1060,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">A. phenomena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[1129,1253,1015,1040]" class="Insecta" family="Clusiidae" genus="Allometopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tropalis">
<emphasis box="[1129,1253,1015,1040]" italics="true" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">A. tropalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1276,1379,1015,1040]" captionStart="FIGURES 284 – 290" captionStartId="118.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1825]" captionTargetId="figure@118.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="FIGURES 284 – 290. Allometopon tropalis Sasakawa, holotype; 284: photo, anterolateral, with detail of vibrissae; 285: same, dorsal; 286: photo, lateral; 287: same, dorsal; 288: paratype, external genitalia, posterior; 289: inner surface of surstylus; 290: internal genitalia, left lateral (from Sasakawa (1974 ))." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258814/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Fig. 
<number box="[1336,1379,1016,1040]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" value="287.0">287</number>
</figureCitation>
) are supported as sister-species, most obviously on the basis of multiplicated vibrissae. The former (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1383,1052,1077]" captionStart="FIGURES 284 – 290" captionStartId="118.[151,264,1876,1899]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,193,1825]" captionTargetId="figure@118.[151,1436,193,1856]" captionTargetPageId="118" captionText="FIGURES 284 – 290. Allometopon tropalis Sasakawa, holotype; 284: photo, anterolateral, with detail of vibrissae; 285: same, dorsal; 286: photo, lateral; 287: same, dorsal; 288: paratype, external genitalia, posterior; 289: inner surface of surstylus; 290: internal genitalia, left lateral (from Sasakawa (1974 ))." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/258814/files/figure.png" pageId="50" pageNumber="51">
Figs 
<number box="[1283,1383,1052,1077]" pageId="50" pageNumber="51" value="284285.0">284, 285</number>
</figureCitation>
) has several pairs of vibrissae arranged horizontally, and the latter has two pairs, with the posterior pair converging and joining apically. Females are unknown for both species so it is uncertain if this is a sex-restricted character. Other supporting features include the shape of the surstylus, which has a circular whorl of spine-like and tubercle-like setae on the inner surface, and the shape of the postgonite and paraphallus. The underlying notal pattern of both is also similar.
</paragraph>
